{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17537607","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17537607"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:18:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:18:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16033"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16033","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16033"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.66,0.18,0.11,0.05,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8724"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68162"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8724"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16033"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53619"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"542"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2118"},{"type":"tags","id":"4466"},{"type":"tags","id":"6356"},{"type":"tags","id":"12176"},{"type":"tags","id":"12184"},{"type":"tags","id":"12806"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20867"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22323"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22812"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68162","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68162"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of worsening lower back pain and fever. She gave birth to her first child five days ago via spontaneous vaginal delivery with epidural anaesthesia. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications other than paracetamol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 125/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. There is marked tenderness over the lumbar spine at the site of epidural insertion. She has no neurological deficits in her lower limbs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 115 g/L (115-160)\u003Cbr /\u003EWhite cell count 16.5 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003Cbr /\u003ENeutrophils 14.2 x 10^9/L (2.0-7.5)\u003Cbr /\u003EC-reactive protein 220 mg/L (\u003C5)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate diagnostic investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Magnetic resonance imaging with contrast","Computed tomography scan of lumbar spine","Ultrasound of spine","Lumbar spine X-ray","Nuclear medicine bone scan"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suspicious for an epidural abscess following epidural anaesthesia during labour. The combination of fever, severe localised back pain, and elevated inflammatory markers in the context of recent epidural insertion requires urgent investigation to confirm the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance imaging with contrast\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard investigation for diagnosing epidural abscess. It provides excellent visualisation of the spinal cord, epidural space, and surrounding soft tissues, allowing accurate identification of the location and extent of any collection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography scan\u003C/strong\u003E is inferior to MRI for evaluating the epidural space and spinal cord. While it may show some changes, it does not provide the soft tissue detail required for surgical planning.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound of spine\u003C/strong\u003E would not be able to adequately visualise deep structures or provide the detailed anatomical information needed to diagnose and plan treatment of an epidural abscess.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELumbar spine X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E has very limited value in diagnosing epidural abscess as it only shows bony changes which occur late in the disease process. It cannot visualise soft tissue infection or early bone involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENuclear medicine bone scan\u003C/strong\u003E would be more appropriate for investigating osteomyelitis but is not the investigation of choice for epidural abscess. It lacks the anatomical detail needed for surgical planning and takes longer to perform than MRI.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEarly recognition and treatment of epidural abscess is crucial as delay can lead to permanent neurological deficits. The most common causative organism is \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E. Treatment typically involves surgical drainage and prolonged intravenous antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Post-epidural abscess should be suspected in patients with fever and back pain following epidural anaesthesia.","MRI with contrast is the gold standard imaging modality for diagnosing epidural abscess.","Early recognition and treatment of epidural abscess is crucial to prevent permanent neurological sequelae."],"references":["Schroeder TH, Krueger WA, Neeser E, Hahn U, Unertl K. Spinal epidural abscess--a rare complication after epidural analgesia for labour and delivery. Br J Anaesth. 2004 Jun;92(6):896-8. doi: 10.1093/bja/aeh152. Epub 2004 Apr 2. PMID: 15064252.","Society of Obstetric Medicine of Australia and New Zealand (SOMANZ). Sepsis in pregnancy: guideline for management [Internet]. 2017 [cited 2024 Nov 21]. Available from: https://www.somanz.org/content/uploads/2020/07/2017SepsisGuidelines.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53619"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16033"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53619"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T13:59:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T14:01:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8724"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68162"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"